MM Update:
I thought I would expand my comments on this, just to try to do it
justice

OPHELIA
Do you doubt that?

LAERTES
For Hamlet and the trifling of his favour,
Hold it a fashion and a toy in blood,
A violet in the youth of primy nature,
Forward, not permanent, sweet, not lasting,
The perfume and suppliance of a minute; No more.

MM:
The Master comes for a &quot;season,&quot; as was mentioned
regarding John the Baptist. Laertes says to take
advantage of the Master, while he is in the body.

MM Update:
What is the &quot;trifling of his favour?&quot;  It's the Master's grace.  If we
are smart, we will try to please the Master, to invoke his grace.
Without his grace, we will remain lost souls, going around in circles
in this wilderness of Satan.  We have been doing that for ages, so
Shakespeare advises us to take advantage of the Master while he is in
the body.

What does &quot;hold it a fashion,&quot; mean?  Fashions come and go.  God comes
and goes.  Sometimes, he comes as a man, sometimes a woman.
Sometimes, he comes as a very loving person.  Sometimes, he comes as a
strict taskmaster.  Sometimes, he gives the teachings clearly and to
the point.  Other times he gives them cryptically.  So, my point is
that God can come in various fashions.  He can come as a Chinaman, an
Arab, an Englishman, an Indian, or even an American.

What does &quot;a toy in blood mean?&quot;  Obviously, a toy is something which
children enjoy.  So, we are like children before the Master.  We
should enjoy his company while it lasts.  &quot;In blood,&quot; clearly means
that the Master is in the body, which is composed of flesh, blood, and
bones.  The Master will only be in the body for a specified period,
known by God.  So, it will behoove us to take advantage of him, while
we are in the body, and he is in the body.

What does &quot;a violet in the youth of primy nature.&quot; mean?  It means
that the Master has a childhood, a youth, a middleage, an oldage, and
a death.  Sometimes, his &quot;season,&quot; i.e. the time allotted to him by
God is so short, that he doesn't even reach old age.  Some Masters,
such as Christ and Marlowe, have died in middle age.  So, the point is
clear, if we don't know how long the Master will be with us, then we
should take advantage of his presence now.

What does &quot;forward,&quot; mean, in this context?  It means that the Master
is always looking forward to going back to the True Home.  It is a
place of unsurpassed beauty and peace.  He doesn't want to remain in
this pigpen of a world any long than he has to.  We should remember
that, and take advantage of his presence now.  Christ said, &quot;I go to
place, where ye cannot come.&quot;  We should work hard on our meditation,
so that we can qualify to reach that place, the True Home.

What does &quot;not permanent,&quot; mean?  It means that he is not permanently
with us.  The body will die and decompose one day, so we should take
advantage of the Master, while he is in the human form with us.

What does &quot;sweet, not lasting,&quot; mean?  It means that the time spent
with the Master is sweet, but it won't last.  That is why we need to
lay up treasure in heaven, and reach the Holy Spirit Form of the
Master.  That form is permanent.  That form will be with the disciple
forever, as Christ said.

What does the last line mean?  The perfume and suppliance of a minute,
no more?  It means that relatively speaking the Master will be gone
shortly.  Vis-a-vis Eternity, the Master is only here for the blink of
an eye.  It is relative.  Satan lulls into thinking that the Master
will be with us for a long time.  He lulls us into procrastination.
He lulls us into putting so many things before the Master, not the
least of which is our own ego.  We might think, well, someday I might
have time for the Master?  Walt Whitman wrote,  &quot;Will you prove too
late.&quot;  If we go to find the Master, and he has already died, then it
will be too late for us.

John 5:33 Ye sent unto John, and he bare witness unto the truth.   34
But I receive not testimony from man: but these things I say, that ye
might be saved.   35 He was a burning and a shining light: and ye were
willing for a season to rejoice in his light.

Michael Martin
